               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300527-214-person1763">
                  JAMES 
                  WILLSON
               <interp inst="t18300527-214-person1763" type="surname" value="WILLSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-214-person1763" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-214-person1763" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I lost my handkerchief on the 21st of May - I was told by Webb that it was taken as I was passing through the <placeName id="t18300527-214-crimeloc1132">Bank-chambers</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18300527-214-crimeloc1132" type="placeName" value="Bank-chambers"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18300527-214-crimeloc1132" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300527-214-off1130 t18300527-214-crimeloc1132"></join> about four o'clock- I did not see the prisoner at all; it was safe about an hour before.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300527-214-person1764">
                  HENRY 
                  WEBB
               <interp inst="t18300527-214-person1764" type="surname" value="WEBB"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-214-person1764" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-214-person1764" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am clerk to a stock-broker. I saw Porter take the handkerchief from the prosecutor's pocket and pass it to Rose, who put it into his pocket - I told the prosecutor; Porter passed the prosecutor - Rose passed me, and was taken by the officer; I went on, and saw Porter tying up his garter - I did not take him, as there were several boys about calling Bill.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. LEE. Q. What time was this? A. Near four o'clock in the Bank-chambers - there were only the prisoners, the prosecutor, and myself; I had never seen Porter before - I had plenty of opportunity of looking at him; he was taken the next day I believe - I suppose five or ten minutes elapsed from the time of his taking it, till I saw him again; he was then in a turning leading to Coleman-street - he walked away from the Bank-chambers; I did not think myself bound to take him - I swear distinctly he is the boy that took it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300527-214-person1765">
                  GEORGE 
                  WILLIAM MORGAN
               <interp inst="t18300527-214-person1765" type="surname" value="WILLIAM MORGAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-214-person1765" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-214-person1765" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am an officer. I saw both the prisoners go down Bartholomew-lane, and cross into Bank-chambers - they followed the prosecutor; Rose came running back just as I got to the gate, and I took him - I do not know that I had seen him before that day, but I knew Porter; I am sure they were together - there were two others who, I suppose, were with them, but they did not go in; when they saw the bustle they ran off. I found the handkerchief on Rose.</p>
               <p>Porter's Defence. I was taking a walk, and this officer took hold of me, and said, "You will soon see your companion, come along with me."</p>
               <p>ROSE - <rs id="t18300527-214-verdict1133" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18300527-214-verdict1133" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 16.</p>
